.TH BRN2 1

.SH NAME
brn2 \- Bulk Rename Files in your preferred text editor

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B brn2
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.br
.B brn2
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \-\- \fI<file1>\fR [\fI<file2>\fR ...]
.br
.B brn2
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fB\-f\fR \fI<filename>\fR
.br
.B brn2
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fB\-d\fR \fI<dir>\fR

.SH DESCRIPTION
brn2 is a fork of brn, a command line tool used to easily mass-rename files
in your preferred text editor. It opens the filenames in a text buffer;
once you edit the names and save/exit the editor, the changes take place
atomically where supported.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display this help message and exit.

.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Verbose mode; output messages (default).

.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Quiet mode; suppress output messages.

.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-implicit
Allow renaming (swapping) files that were not explicitly provided in the
list of files.

.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-explicit
Only rename files given in the list (default).

.TP
.BR \-F ", " \-\-fatal
Exit on the first renaming error encountered.

.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-autosolve
Auto solve name conflicts for files with identical content. If a new name
matches an existing file with the same content, the existing file is
removed to allow the rename.

.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-sort
Disable sorting of the original file list.

.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-vim-split
Use vim in vertical split mode.

.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.B No arguments
Rename files in the current working directory.

.TP
.B 1 or more arguments
Rename filenames passed as arguments.

.TP
.BR \-d " \fI<dir>\fR, " \-\-dir= \fI<dir>\fR
Rename files within the specified directory.

.TP
.BR \-f " \fI<file>\fR, " \-\-file= \fI<file>\fR
Rename filenames listed in the specified file. Use \fB-\fR or \fB/dev/stdin\fR
to read from standard input.

.SH NOTES
.TP
.B Editor Selection
Uses the \fB$EDITOR\fR environment variable. If not set, it defaults to \fBvim\fR.

.TP
.B Normalization
Filenames are normalized before being presented:
leading \fB./\fR is removed, consecutive slashes are bundled,
and trailing slashes are added to denote directories.

.TP
.B Swapping
On GNU/Linux, \fBbrn2\fR uses the \fBrenameat2\fR system call to atomically
swap filenames without temporary files. On other systems, swapping will
safely fail without renaming.

.TP
.B Limitations
Does not support more than 2^31 renames at once. Filenames cannot exceed
4096 bytes. Newlines in filenames are strictly prohibited.
Filenames containing only dots and slashes are ignored.

.TP
.B Renaming in Depth
Exercise caution when renaming parent directories and their children
simultaneously (e.g., \fIdir/\fR and \fIdir/file\fR). Renaming a parent
directory first will cause subsequent renames of its children to fail.
It is recommended to rename regular files first, or operate in steps
from the deepest path upwards.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred (e.g., file not found, permission denied, or fatal error
triggered).

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B brn2 *.jpg
Rename all JPG files in the current directory.
.TP
.B find . -type f | brn2 -f -
Recursively find all regular files and rename them.

